                           SLEWING                           
     In slew mode, you can move the plane freely and quickly in 3D
space using the mouse and keyboard controls. You can change  
your heading, bank, and pitch. You can instantaneosly stop   
the plane in mid air and look around.                        
     Enter slew mode by selecting SLEW on the NAV menu. Slewing   
can be fully controlled from the keyboard. Some slew movement
can be controlled by the mouse. Moving the mouse forward and 
backward accelerates you forward and backward. The more you  
move the mouse, the faster you will accelerate. Left and     
right mouse movement change the direction you are pointing.  
     You can "steer" yourself as you move forward. Single-clicking
the mouse stops all slew motion, while double-clicking       
returns you to cursor mode.                                  
     To control slew movement from the keyboard, use the numeric  
keypad. The[8] and [2] keys accelerate forward and backward. 
The [4] and [6] keys turn left and right. The [5] key stops  
all slew movement.                                           

     The following keys control other slew directions:            
< = Left                                                     
> = Right                                                    
Q = Increase altitude                                        
A = Decrease altitude                                        
[ = Left bank                                                
] = Right bank                                               
Z = Turn On/Off North and East digit readouts                
     As you slew around, the values next to the NORTH and EAST    
parameters change to reflect your new position. When you     
resume flight, you will resume from the new north and east   
positions.                                                   
     Exit slew mode by clicking on the SLEW item on the NAV menu. 
This will put you back into flight mode.                     

                        POSITION SET                         
     This function changes the default airport when you enter new 
North, East, and also altitude coodinantes.                  

                    RADIO SHACK CONTROLS                     
NAV1 and NAV2 radios are for Vor1 and Vor2. DME radio tells  
you how many nautical miles you are away from Vor1.          
Communication and transponder radios along with NAV1 and NAV2
are set by using the mouse and cursor mode and just clicking 
the digits you want to change. Also the onboard clock can be 
set the same way.                                            
